</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1155,1130,1294]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">
(
<figureCitation box="[167,265,1166,1190]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="6.[160,225,1613,1636]" captionTargetBox="[236,1079,142,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-1@6.[236,1079,142,1582]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 3. A. hispida, (a) habitus; (b) longitudinal section (abbreviations: mb, the main bundle in the inner part of the sponge; s, styles, branching off from the main bundle and penetrating the surface); (c–e) SEM images of spicules; (c) long style; (d) flexuous oxea; (e) thick style." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4780300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4780300/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Figure 3</figureCitation>
(a)) Body elongated, branching or lobate, size up to 
<quantity box="[895,975,1166,1190]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="495" unit="cm" value="9.5">9.5 cm</quantity>
in height. It is slightly narrowing downwards forming a short peduncle. Surface setose, markedly hispid, covered with a thin, pellucid aspicular dermal membrane. The consistency is quite strong and elastic. Colour ash-yellow or greenish yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[160,1156,1356,1450]" box="[160,261,1356,1381]" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,261,1356,1381]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="495">Skeleton</emphasis>
</paragraph>
